export const EVIDENCE: Record<string,{source:string;text:string}> = {"S-001":{"source":"Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","text":""},"S-002":{"source":"A ten-year strategy for the operating system of the physical world","text":"Classification: Board & Strategy Committee · dual-listing readiness · Office of the CEO Prepared with: Strategy, Finance, and the Data/AI Platform group Length: long-form — one thesis, six domains, dissected to the mechanism level and cross-linked into a single flywheel. Built to be read top-down and drilled into."},"S-003":{"source":"The answer, before the argument","text":"The market looks at Kepler and sees a conglomerate: six physical-world businesses — mobility, energy, logistics, payments, devices, and the data platform beneath them — stapled together under one brand, each trailing a focused specialist in its own vertical, the whole priced at a ~35% conglomerate discount to the sum of its parts. On that reading, the obvious move is to break Kepler up: spin the six out, let each compete on its own, unlock the discount.\n\nThat reading is wrong, and this document exists to prove it wrong at the mechanism level. Kepler is not six businesses. It is one flywheel. Every physical-world interaction it touches — a ride requested, a battery charged, a parcel delivered, a payment cleared, a device pinged — produces data and network effects that no single-vertical competitor can assemble, because no single-vertical competitor touches the physical world across all si"},"S-004":{"source":"Situation, Complication, Question","text":"Situation. Kepler is real and at scale: 42 cities across 14 countries, 28.4m monthly actives, $9.4bn revenue. Six operating domains, each a genuine business with genuine customers. On raw scale, few physical-world platforms on earth are comparable.\n\nComplication. Judged as six separate businesses, Kepler is mediocre in every one — it is not the mobility leader, not the payments leader, not the logistics leader, in any single market. It runs at −420m cost centre with no P&L of its own, and the market applies the ~35% conglomerate discount precisely because it cannot see the connective tissue. The sum-of-parts case for a break-up is, on the surface, strong.\n\nQuestion. Are these six businesses to be spun apart for focus and to unlock the discount — or are they one flywheel to be sequenced together? And if the flywheel is real, in what order must the domains be built, and with what proof tha"},"S-005":{"source":"The spine — one moat, four terms, six feeders","text":"Every claim in this document ties back to one identity. The strength of Kepler's moat is the product of four terms:\n\nIt is a product, not a sum — which is the entire strategic point. A conglomerate adds four mediocre terms and gets mediocrity. A flywheel multiplies them, and multiplication means the weakest term caps the moat and each domain that lifts one term lifts the whole product. No single domain moves all four; each owns or feeds specific terms, and the cross-feeds between them are the flywheel made concrete:\n\nToday M is sub-scale, not because any term is absent, but because the six domains hoard their data in separate warehouses — the terms are added, not multiplied. The strategy is to wire the cross-feeds and sequence the build so the terms compound. The measurable target: lift blended contribution per interaction from −0.31 over ten years, driven not by any single domain's marg"},"S-006":{"source":"How to read this document","text":"It is built the way the argument is built: top-down, then drilled into, then reassembled.\n\nLevel 1 — the answer is above: one flywheel, not six businesses; sequencing is the whole game; the moat is M = D × B × L × T.\n\nLevel 2 — the six domains, one section each. Each opens by naming which moat term(s) it owns or feeds, and its cross-links.\n\nLevel 3 — the drivers. Each domain decomposes into four drivers — the distinct forces inside it.\n\nLevel 4 — the mechanisms and their evidence. Each driver opens into the specific mechanisms that move the number, with the maps, mockups, models, code, and data that prove it. This is where the compounding is real or it is a story.\n\nTwo instructions for the reader. First, the couplings are the argument — each domain section names how it feeds and is fed by the others; a reader who reads the six as standalone chapters has missed the entire thesis, because "},"S-007":{"source":"Domain 1 — Autonomous Mobility: the density engine that feeds everything else","text":"Mobility is where Kepler touches the physical world most often, and frequency is the point. In the moat identity M = D × B × L × T, this domain owns Interaction density (D) outright — the sheer count of geolocated, time-stamped, behaviourally-rich events per square kilometre per hour — and it is the only domain that manufactures D at industrial scale. Every ride is a probe: it measures a street, a curb, a queue, a payment, a rider's tolerance for a three-minute wait. At 41% of the $9.4bn top line, mobility is also the cash and data furnace that the other five draw on. The argument of this section is narrow and load-bearing: D is not a vanity metric; it is the raw feedstock that lowers cost and raises trust everywhere else, and mobility is the only domain that can move it by an order of magnitude.\n\nThe cross-feeds are the whole reason D matters. Mobility's dwell-and-idle heatmaps tell Ene"},"S-008":{"source":"Driver 1 — The fleet and the density engine","text":"Density is not bought; it is compounded. The fleet is the physical instrument that converts capital into interactions, and the discipline is concentrating that instrument until the data it produces crosses a usefulness threshold, then holding it there while demand catches up."},"S-009":{"source":"The density-first deployment rule","text":"Kepler does not spread vehicles to maximise city coverage; it floods zones until interaction density per km² per hour crosses the threshold where the routing and pricing models stop guessing. Below roughly 40 interactions/km²/hr the models are extrapolating; above it they are interpolating, and every downstream prediction — ETA, surge, charger dwell — sharpens. The mechanism moves D directly: rather than 300 vehicles thin across a metro, Kepler runs 1,100 inside three contiguous zones. The number it moves is the map utilization figure below; the trade-off is brutal and deliberate — visible under-service at the metro edge, and a press narrative of \"Kepler abandoned the suburbs,\" accepted because a dense core produces data that a thin blanket never will (S-101).\n\nThe geo/fleet MAP renders the rule. Read it as a metro canvas with named zones as filled polygons, each labelled with active veh"},"S-010":{"source":"Holding the floor with a utilization time-series","text":"Concentration only compounds if utilization stays high enough that the fleet is interacting rather than idling — an idle AV produces no D and burns the depreciation that Driver 4 quantifies. Kepler manages the fleet against a utilization floor, dispatching repositioning moves and dynamic pricing (fed by D4's cash-free rails) whenever a zone threatens to slip beneath it. The mechanism moves D by protecting the denominator of interactions-per-vehicle; the number it moves is weekday utilization, held above the 60% floor in saturated zones.\n\nThe utilization TIME-SERIES for Marina Core, plotted as a 24-hour curve (x-axis midnight-to-midnight, y-axis utilization %, a dashed 60% floor line):\n\nTwo peaks (07:30 and 18:15) clear 80%; the 14:00 midday trough kisses the floor and triggers repositioning and a fare cut (S-103). The edge-case is the trough that breaks the floor — a rain-driven demand c"},"S-011":{"source":"Driver 2 — Safety and the trust it earns","text":"Density without safety is a liability that regulators close overnight. This driver owns mobility's contribution to Trust (T) — the only term besides D that mobility meaningfully moves — and the mechanism is turning accumulated safe miles into a disclosed, auditable record that regulators and riders both price in."},"S-012":{"source":"Miles-per-intervention as the trust currency","text":"The operating metric is miles between safety-critical disengagements (a remote operator or safety driver taking control to avoid harm). Density helps here in a way competitors cannot copy: saturated zones generate so many miles over the same road geometry that the model sees each rare edge-case — an occluded pedestrian, a jaywalking cyclist against the light — hundreds of times rather than once. The mechanism moves T by pushing miles-per-intervention up an order of magnitude, and it is fed by D6's perception models, which are themselves trained on the density D1 produces (S-105). The trade-off is that chasing the metric too hard breeds over-cautious \"freezing\" behaviour that tanks the rider experience of Driver 3 — so the safety and experience teams share one objective function, not two.\n\nMiles/intervention rose 11.6× across four quarters while fleet miles merely tripled — the superlinea"},"S-013":{"source":"The incident timeline as an auditable record","text":"Trust is not the average; it is how the worst days are handled and disclosed. Kepler maintains a public safety-incident TIMELINE — every safety-critical event logged, root-caused, and tied to the model or hardware change that closed it. The mechanism moves T by converting opaque risk into an audit trail regulators can inspect before granting the next zone permit (S-107). The trade-off is radical transparency: disclosing incidents competitors keep quiet, a short-term reputational cost paid for long-term licence-to-operate.\n\nThe Q4 event is the instructive edge-case: heavy rain attenuated lidar, the vehicle correctly executed a minimum-risk pullover rather than proceeding blind, and the fix — radar-weighted sensor fusion — came straight from Devices (D5) hardware co-design (S-109). The chain to Driver 3: a fleet that is both dense and demonstrably safe can finally be sold as an experience,"},"S-014":{"source":"Driver 3 — The rider experience","text":"D and T are supply-side; they convert to revenue only through a rider who chooses Kepler again. This driver is where interaction density becomes interaction loyalty — where the density flywheel either self-reinforces (more riders → more D → better predictions → better experience → more riders) or stalls. Mobility's role here is to raise D by lifting ride frequency per rider, and the lever is a rider app that turns model precision into felt reliability."},"S-015":{"source":"Precision ETAs as the retention engine","text":"The single experience variable that most moves rebooking is ETA accuracy — not speed, accuracy. A rider forgives a four-minute wait promised as four minutes; they abandon a three-minute wait promised as one. Density feeds this directly: saturated zones let the ETA model interpolate from dense recent history rather than extrapolate, cutting mean absolute ETA error. The mechanism moves D by lifting rides-per-active-rider (frequency is density), and it is fed by D6's demand models and the origin-destination tensor mobility itself generates (S-110). The trade-off is that guaranteeing tight ETAs sometimes means pre-positioning idle vehicles, which nicks the utilization floor of Driver 1 — a managed tension, priced.\n\nThe rider-app MOCKUP, first as a push notification landing on a lock screen:\n\nThen the in-app ride screen the rider sees after tapping through:\n\nThe copy is doing three jobs: \"1,2"},"S-016":{"source":"The origin-destination tensor as the shared demand prior","text":"Every completed ride writes one cell into an origin-destination-by-time tensor — the densest demand map anyone in these cities holds. The mechanism moves D by making the next rider's experience better (the tensor is the prior every ETA and surge decision reads from), and its cross-feeds are the flywheel's spine: the same tensor is the demand prior Logistics (D3) routes couriers against and the dwell-pattern input Energy (D2) sites chargers from (S-112). The trade-off is privacy exposure — the tensor is re-identification-sensitive, so it is aggregated and differentially private before it leaves the mobility boundary, a deliberate loss of resolution accepted for trust. The chain to Driver 4: an experience this reliable is only defensible if the machine underneath earns money per ride, which is where unit economics decide whether density is an asset or a subsidy."},"S-017":{"source":"Driver 4 — The vehicle and unit economics","text":"Density that loses money is a countdown, not a moat. This driver asks whether each incremental interaction is accretive, and answers with the vehicle itself — the sensor stack that makes autonomy possible is also the cost line that decides the flywheel's terminal contribution. Mobility moves D here only insofar as the per-ride economics let Kepler hold the density rather than retreat from it."},"S-018":{"source":"The teardown — sensor cost as the swing variable","text":"The AV is a rolling sensor platform, and its bill of materials is the largest lever on contribution/interaction. The vehicle EXPLODED/TEARDOWN diagram, components named and exploded outward from the chassis:\n\nThe teardown maps one-to-one to the safety timeline: the Q4 rain incident's fix — radar-weighted fusion — is why the 4D imaging radar count is five, not three (S-113). Every one of these sensors is co-designed with Devices (D5), and their raw streams are the proprietary telemetry that widens Data breadth (B) for D6's models — mobility manufactures D, but the vehicle is where it hands B to the platform (S-114). The BOM cost table, the swing variable in one view:\n\nLidar is 61% of the sensor bill and the entire cost thesis: the solid-state roadmap that roughly halves the stack to ~$6,900 is what flips per-ride contribution positive at current density (S-115). The trade-off is timing — "},"S-019":{"source":"Contribution per interaction — the flywheel's scoreboard","text":"The number that ties this domain to the bible's central promise is blended contribution/interaction, which the flywheel is chartered to lift from −0.31 over ten years. Mobility's job is to drive its share of that swing through two chained effects: density raises utilization (Driver 1) which amortises the vehicle across more paid minutes, and the sensor stream widens B (this driver) which sharpens the fraud, routing, and siting models that lower cost in D2/D3/D4. The mechanism moves D's value, not its count — the same interaction is worth more once four other domains monetise it. The cross-feed made concrete: mobility's trajectory-plus-device-fingerprint stream is the strongest single input to Payments (D4) fraud scoring, and each fraud dollar D4 saves is booked partly against the ride that generated the signal (S-116). The edge-case is the loss-leader ride — a deliberately under-priced t"},"S-020":{"source":"What's true vs what counts","text":"What's true. On its own numbers, Kepler mobility is a strong-but-not-singular robotaxi operation. It runs a dense, safe, well-instrumented fleet; utilization in saturated zones clears 70%; miles-per-intervention improved 11.6× in a year; the rider app is good. A focused robotaxi specialist could match most of this line by line, and on a sum-of-the-parts read the market would be right to price mobility as one competent vertical inside a discounted conglomerate. The sensor stack still loses money per ride until solid-state lidar lands. None of this, standing alone, is uncatchable.\n\nWhat counts. Mobility is the only domain that manufactures Interaction density (D) at scale, and D is the feedstock the entire flywheel runs on. The dwell heatmaps that site Energy (D2) chargers before demand exists (S-118); the origin-destination tensor that Logistics (D3) routes against (S-119); the trajectory"},"S-021":{"source":"Domain 2 — Energy & Charging: the cost floor and the reliability that earns trust","text":"Energy is the domain that almost nobody underwrites correctly, because on a standalone P&L it looks like the worst business we own: capital-heavy, thin-margined, exposed to a commodity we do not control. Read against the moat identity, though, it is the domain that quietly sets the floor under everything else. Of the four moat terms — M = D × B × L × T — Energy & Charging moves exactly two, and it moves them in a way no other domain can. It compresses the marginal cost of every electron-consuming interaction in the flywheel, and it manufactures Trust (T) the only way trust in physical infrastructure is ever actually manufactured: by being reliable ten thousand times in a row where a competitor is reliable nine thousand nine hundred. It does not touch interaction density (D — that is D1's job), it feeds but does not own data breadth (B — that is D5/D6), and it is agnostic to network liqui"},"S-022":{"source":"Driver 1 — The charging network as an asset","text":"The first driver is the physical network itself: 6,180 charging sites across the 42 cities, and the question of whether that estate is a cost sink or a compounding asset. The answer turns entirely on where the sites are, which is where the first cross-domain coupling does its work."},"S-023":{"source":"Mechanism 1.1 — Siting fed by Mobility's location data (D1 → D2)","text":"A standalone charge-point operator sites capacity against traffic counts and grid-connection availability — public, laggy, and available to every competitor simultaneously. Kepler sites capacity against D1's proprietary dwell-and-dispatch map: where autonomous vehicles actually idle between fares, where riders actually originate, where the fleet's state-of-charge actually crosses the reorder threshold. This is the flywheel's first turn in the energy domain. Because D1 generates the densest location and behaviour data in the network, we can place a fast-charger on the corner where the fleet will need it in 2027, not the corner that looked busy in 2024. [S-201] In the eleven cities where siting has been driven by D1 telemetry rather than public traffic data, first-year utilization ran 31% higher than in the legacy-sited estate — the single largest driver of site-level payback in the portfo"},"S-024":{"source":"Mechanism 1.2 — Vertical integration of the power economics","text":"A well-sited, dual-fed estate is worth owning up the stack. Because we can forecast aggregate load with the fleet data behind Mechanism 1.1, we can contract power as an industrial buyer — long-dated PPAs, wholesale-market participation, on-site storage — rather than paying retail tariffs at each socket. [S-203] Blended landed cost of energy across the network is $0.081/kWh versus a retail benchmark of $0.163/kWh in the same metros: a 50.3% wholesale-plus discount that is the raw material of the cost floor. This is the mechanism that converts \"we own chargers\" into \"we own the marginal cost of movement,\" and it is the hinge for the entire domain, because that $0.082/kWh gap is what gets handed to D1 and D3."},"S-025":{"source":"Driver 2 — Load, demand & dispatch","text":"Owning cheap electrons is necessary but not sufficient. The second driver is the operational engine that decides when to buy, when to charge, and what to price — the machinery that turns a cheap average cost into a cheap marginal cost at the moment of each interaction. This is where the domain's distinctive formula-and-code palette lives."},"S-026":{"source":"Mechanism 2.1 — Reading the load curve","text":"Demand is not flat, and the shape of the curve is the whole game. Two patterns dominate.\n\nLoad/demand CHART — daily curve (network-average kW drawn, normalised to peak = 100):\n\nTwo peaks — a sharp morning ramp (06:00–09:00, fleet pre-positioning + commuter charging) and a taller, longer evening peak (17:00–21:00, fleet recharge + courier surge + retail). The trough is 00:00–05:00, when landed cost is lowest and demand is thinnest. The economic opportunity is the gap between the two.\n\nLoad/demand CHART — seasonal (monthly peak-load index, network, base = Jan 100):\n\nTwo seasonal ridges: a cooling-driven summer peak (Jun–Aug) in the tropical metros where grid prices spike with air-conditioning load, and a Q4 logistics peak driven by D3's delivery surge. [S-204] These two ridges do not coincide with cheap-power windows, which is precisely why dispatch — not just procurement — is where margin"},"S-027":{"source":"Mechanism 2.2 — Dynamic pricing and dispatch optimisation","text":"Given the curve, the engine does two coupled things: it prices demand to flatten the peaks, and it dispatches charging (and stored energy) into the troughs. Both run off one margin object.\n\nPricing/dispatch FORMULA. The per-session price is a base landed cost plus a congestion term that rises with local utilisation and a scarcity term that rises with grid price, floored to protect trust and capped to protect it too:\n\nwhere util(s,t) ∈ [0,1] is site utilisation, grid(t) is the live wholesale price, and β, γ are tuned per city. The dispatch side solves, over a rolling 24h horizon, when to draw from storage vs. the grid to minimise landed cost subject to meeting the forecast load:\n\n[S-205] With this engine live, peak-to-trough load has flattened by 18 points of the normalised index versus flat-tariff baseline, and storage arbitrage captured $0.019/kWh of additional margin on the 22% of volu"},"S-028":{"source":"Driver 3 — Reliability & the trust it buys","text":"The third driver is the one the standalone financial model cannot see, because reliability shows up as an absence — the charge that did not fail, the queue that did not form, the trip the fleet did not have to abort. Reliability is how Energy moves the T term, and T is the term with the longest cross-domain reach."},"S-029":{"source":"Mechanism 3.1 — Uptime as the atomic unit of trust","text":"Trust in physical infrastructure is not a brand attribute; it is an empirical frequency. A user trusts the network to the exact degree that it works when they arrive. So we instrument it obsessively.\n\nUtilization GAUGE dashboard — the operating health of the estate at a glance:\n\n[S-208] Network uptime sits at 99.2% against a 99.0% target and an industry field average nearer 96%; session-success (a plug-in that ends in a completed charge) is 98.6%. The three-point gap between our uptime and the industry field average is not a bragging right — it is the raw material of T. [S-209] In cohort data, a user whose first three sessions all succeeded shows a 4.1× higher 90-day retention than one who hit an early failed session, and — critically — a 2.3× higher rate of activating the D4 wallet. The failed charge does not just cost one session; it poisons the trust that Payments was going to draw on"},"S-030":{"source":"Mechanism 3.2 — Reliability feeds T that Payments (D4) relies on","text":"This is the coupling that justifies housing energy and payments under one roof. Trust earned at the socket is fungible in the user's mind: the person who has learned that the Kepler charger always works is measurably more willing to let the Kepler wallet hold a balance, auto-pay, and eventually accept a credit line. [S-210] We can trace it in the funnel — of users who reached \"high-trust\" status via a clean charging history, 58% enabled auto-pay within 60 days versus 29% of the general base, and their D4 fraud-dispute rate ran 40% lower (reliable-infrastructure users are, empirically, lower-risk users). Energy is therefore a T-acquisition channel for Payments, and it is cheaper than any marketing D4 could run, because the trust is a by-product of a charge the user was going to buy anyway. The mechanism chains forward one last time: if reliability is the asset that buys trust, then the du"},"S-031":{"source":"Driver 4 — The energy-transition scenario","text":"The final driver is the ten-year question: does the cost floor and the trust ceiling survive a decarbonising, re-pricing grid? Energy is the one domain whose core input — the wholesale price of electricity — is set by forces outside Kepler entirely. We therefore model the domain not as a point forecast but as a tree of grid-price paths, each mapped to a margin outcome."},"S-032":{"source":"Mechanism 4.1 — The scenario tree from grid price to margin","text":"Energy SCENARIO TREE (10-year, branching on grid-price path → renewables mix → net domain contribution margin):\n\n[S-211] The probability-weighted expected margin across the tree is +$0.036/kWh, and — the decisive feature — five of six branches are margin-positive. The single negative branch (Squeeze: rising grid and PPAs repricing against us) carries only ~6% weight because our long-dated PPA book and storage hedge (Mechanism 2.2) are precisely the instruments that collapse it. [S-212] Note also that the two \"Grid rises\" branches, painful for margin, are helpful for the cost-advantage spread: when retail power spikes, our hedged landed cost spikes far less, so the gap we hand to D1 and D3 actually widens — the domain's cross-domain value is counter-cyclical to its own P&L. This is why the scenario tree matters strategically and not just financially: even the branches that hurt the standa"},"S-033":{"source":"Mechanism 4.2 — Siting and dispatch as the hedge against the tree","text":"The tree is not something we merely await; the first three drivers are the instruments that bias us toward its upper branches. Data-led siting (1.1) concentrates the estate where renewables and storage are scaling fastest; vertical procurement (1.2) locks the PPAs that hold in the \"Grid rises\" branch; dispatch optimisation (2.2) is literally the mechanism that converts a \"Volatile-Thin\" world into a \"Volatile-Win\" one by arbitraging the peaks. Reliability (3.x) ensures that whatever branch we land in, the trust output — and therefore the D4 coupling — is preserved. Every driver in this section is simultaneously an operating lever and a hedge on the transition tree, which is the property we most want from an infrastructure asset facing a decade of grid re-pricing."},"S-034":{"source":"What's true vs what counts","text":"What's true. Energy & Charging is, on its own books, the least attractive standalone business in the portfolio: capital-intensive, exposed to a commodity it cannot control, and margin-thin even in its good branches (probability-weighted +$0.036/kWh is a utility-grade number, not a software one). A focused charge-point specialist, unburdened by the rest of Kepler, would likely operate a leaner balance sheet and trade at a cleaner multiple. All of that is true, and it is why the sum-of-the-parts view marks this domain down.\n\nWhat counts. None of that is the point of owning it. What counts is that Energy moves two moat terms — cost and T — and moves them for the whole flywheel. It sets a $0.082/kWh cost floor under D1 and D3 that widens exactly when the grid gets expensive, siting itself off D1's location data so the asset is placed where the network will actually need it. And it manufactur"},"S-035":{"source":"Domain 3 — Logistics Marketplace: liquidity is the product","text":"Domain 3 is the only Kepler business whose moat term you can watch move in real time. It owns network liquidity (L) — the probability that, at any given moment in any given cell of any of our 42 cities, a courier and a merchant order can be matched inside the time and price window that both sides will accept. Mobility (D1) owns density, Devices (D5) own breadth, Payments (D4) and Energy (D2) own trust; Logistics owns the term that turns a pile of supply and a pile of demand into a market. And L is the most fragile of the four, because it is not a stock we accumulate but a flow we defend every fifteen minutes. A city can have thousands of couriers and thousands of hungry merchants and still be illiquid — if they are in the wrong places, priced wrong, or matched slowly, the market clears at 61% and both sides quietly churn. Liquidity is not headcount. Liquidity is the product, and everythi"},"S-036":{"source":"Driver 1 — Two-sided liquidity: the core marketplace dynamic","text":"Liquidity is the reflexive loop every marketplace lives or dies inside, and stating it precisely is the whole discipline. More couriers online → shorter pickup ETAs and fewer unfulfilled orders → higher merchant satisfaction and order volume → more and denser earnings opportunities per online hour → more couriers online. The loop runs in reverse just as fast: a thin week thins the other side within two weeks. Our job is to bias the loop forward at the lowest subsidy cost, and to know — cell by cell, hour by hour — exactly where on the liquidity curve each market sits."},"S-037":{"source":"Mechanism 1.1 — The liquidity composite and the two-sided funnel","text":"We refuse to manage liquidity as a single \"orders\" number because that number hides the two independent conversion pipelines feeding it. We instrument both sides as a two-sided conversion funnel, and the shape of each side tells us which piston is misfiring (S-305).\n\nThe funnel makes the pathology legible. The courier side hemorrhages between \"first shift\" and \"4+ shifts\" — the moment a new courier learns whether the app can actually feed them enough well-paid jobs to bother. That 58%→39% cliff is a liquidity problem masquerading as a retention problem: couriers churn not because onboarding is hard but because the market was thin the week they tried it. The merchant side leaks worst at \"first order taken\" → \"10+ orders\" for the symmetric reason: a restaurant that lists and then waits twenty minutes for a courier on its first lunch rush concludes we don't work. Both cliffs are the same cl"},"S-038":{"source":"Mechanism 1.2 — Cohort retention as the liquidity truth serum","text":"Because the funnel is a snapshot, we govern the business on cohort-retention curves — the honest, un-gameable record of whether each side stuck. The shapes are as diagnostic as the numbers.\n\nTwo facts govern the plan. First, the merchant curve flattens high — merchants that survive their first month churn at under 3%/month, because a restaurant that has integrated us into its lunch service faces real switching cost and, critically, because D4 working-capital advances (settled against observed flow) make Kepler a lender as well as a channel. That flat tail is where merchant lifetime value lives. Second, the courier curve smiles — it decays, then stabilizes around a hard core of professional couriers doing 30+ hours/week who account for 68% of delivered volume from 19% of the retained cohort (S-307). These two shapes dictate opposite tactics: for merchants, win month one and the curve hold"},"S-039":{"source":"Driver 2 — Courier supply: manufacturing the sell side","text":"Couriers are half the market and the more volatile half, because their participation is priced by the hour against every other earning option in the city. Supply is not recruited once; it is summoned order by order, which is why the courier-facing surface — the app in a rider's hand — is a first-class strategic asset, not a UI afterthought."},"S-040":{"source":"Mechanism 2.1 — The job-offer surface: earning legible in one screen","text":"A courier decides to accept or decline in under four seconds. Everything that determines whether L holds — the guaranteed payout, the honest ETA, the surge multiplier, the batching — has to be legible in that window. Here is the live in-app job-offer screen and the push that precedes it, real production copy (S-308):\n\nEvery element is a liquidity lever with a cross-feed behind it. The €14.20 is guaranteed, not estimated — the courier is paid that number even if the drop runs long, which is only underwritable because D4 pays out in nine seconds and D6 predicts route time tightly enough that our guarantee variance is ±7%. The \"~22 min\" and \"5.4 km\" are honest because D1 mobility traces give congestion-real ETAs (S-309); a competitor quoting optimistic times trains its couriers to distrust the app, which is precisely the 58%→39% funnel cliff in miniature. The \"bike at 88%\" line ties to D2 —"},"S-041":{"source":"Mechanism 2.2 — Supply elasticity and the cost of the marginal hour","text":"The professional core is inelastic and cheap; the casual tail is elastic and expensive, summoned only when demand spikes past what the core can clear. We model the marginal cost of an online courier-hour by tier and use it to price surge (Driver 4). The table is the supply curve made operational:\n\nThe strategy reads straight off the table (S-310): protect the core's effective pay at almost any cost — losing 1% of them costs disproportionate volume — and use the casual tail's high elasticity as a supply valve, dialing surge to pull it online for the two hours a day it is needed and letting it recede otherwise. The failure mode we design against is subsidizing the whole population to solve a problem that lives in the tail, which is how standalone marketplaces burn cash into a thin market. Because D2 lowers the core's real energy cost and D4 lowers their payout friction to zero, Kepler's co"},"S-042":{"source":"Driver 3 — The matching engine: converting both sides into cleared orders","text":"Supply and demand do not clear themselves. The matching engine is the crankshaft — the code that, every few seconds, looks at every open order and every available courier in a cell and decides who gets what. Its objective function is the liquidity composite. A naive nearest-courier matcher looks fine at low load and collapses under surge, because greedy local matches strand distant orders; the engine has to optimize the market, not the order."},"S-043":{"source":"Mechanism 3.1 — Batch-optimal assignment, not greedy nearest","text":"The engine runs on a short dispatch tick, batching open orders and idle couriers into a bipartite assignment problem solved for a blended cost of ETA, batching gain, courier fairness, and predicted acceptance. The pseudocode is the actual shape of the loop (S-311):\n\nFour cross-feeds are load-bearing inside one function. D1_travel_time replaces straight-line distance with congestion-real ETA — the single biggest match-quality gain, worth +9pts of fill rate in dense cells (S-312). D6_accept_model predicts, per courier per batch, the probability of acceptance, so the engine offers each job to the courier most likely to take it and do it well, which cuts decline-and-reoffer churn that otherwise adds 40–90s of latency per order. D2_energy_ok refuses to hand a courier a batch their charge can't finish. And fairness_debt protects the professional core's earnings from being starved by the optimi"},"S-044":{"source":"Mechanism 3.2 — The engine as the compounding surface","text":"The matcher is where the flywheel compounds fastest, because every completed and every declined offer is a labeled training example fed straight back to D6. Match quality this quarter trains the acceptance model that raises match quality next quarter (S-313). This is the mechanism by which L stops being a subsidy we buy and becomes a moat we own: a competitor can match our price for a week, but cannot match a model trained on 340 million dispatch decisions per month across six correlated domains. The gap between our fill rate and a well-funded standalone's has widened from 4pts to 11pts over eight quarters at equal courier pay — not because we spend more, but because the engine has learned more (S-314)."},"S-045":{"source":"Driver 4 — Merchant demand and density: the buy side and the geometry","text":"Demand is the other piston, and it has a spatial dimension supply does not: a merchant is a fixed point, and the density of merchants and orders in a cell determines whether batching — the single biggest efficiency lever — is even possible. Thin, spread-out demand cannot be batched, so it is expensive to serve at any courier count. Dense demand is self-lubricating."},"S-046":{"source":"Mechanism 4.1 — Density as the batching multiplier","text":"Below a critical order density the engine cannot stack drops, so every order consumes a whole courier trip; above it, three drops share one trip and effective supply triples without one extra courier. We manage cities across this threshold explicitly:\n\nThe non-linearity is the whole strategy (S-315). The jump from \"approaching\" to \"liquid\" flips contribution from negative to positive on a batching multiplier, not a price change. So the growth playbook is not \"add cities\" but \"concentrate demand within a city until cells cross the batching threshold, then widen\" — a land-and-densify motion, using D1 mobility data to know exactly which cells already have the foot traffic to support density before we spend a euro of merchant acquisition (S-316). Kepler's cross-domain advantage is that Mobility has already mapped the demand geography of all 42 cities, so Logistics launches into pre-validated"},"S-047":{"source":"Mechanism 4.2 — Surge as the equilibrium regulator","text":"When demand spikes past available supply, price is the only fast lever — surge pulls the elastic casual tail online (Driver 2) and, secondarily, rations demand. The supply–demand equilibrium chart is the control surface the surge engine reads (S-317):\n\nRead left to right: at the pre-surge point ○, peak demand D_peak sits far right of base supply S₀, which is nearly vertical because the inelastic core won't add hours for a small bump — so the market can't clear, fill collapses to 71%, ETAs blow out, and both funnels start leaking within the hour. Surge shifts supply to S₁ by paying the elastic tail enough to come online, moving the clearing point to ★ at 96% fill. The engine's raise_surge call (Mechanism 3.1) is literally walking this curve, using the Driver-2 elasticity table to choose the smallest multiplier that reaches ★. Set surge too low and the market stays illiquid; too high and y"},"S-048":{"source":"What's true vs what counts","text":"What's true. Logistics is 18% of revenue, growing +34% yoy, roughly contribution-neutral today at +€0.04/order. The two-sided funnel leaks hard at the same cliff on both sides. The courier retention curve smiles and the merchant curve flattens high. A professional core of 19% of couriers does 68% of volume. Contribution flips positive only above the batching-density threshold. All of that is real, measured, and — read as a standalone marketplace — describes a competent-but-unremarkable delivery business trailing the category leader on scale.\n\nWhat counts. None of those facts is the point. The point is that Logistics owns L, the one moat term you can watch clear or fail to clear every fifteen minutes, and that L is manufactured almost entirely out of the other five domains: routing from D1, cheap energy from D2, instant cash-free settlement and merchant credit from D4, and a matching engi"},"S-049":{"source":"Domain 4 — Payments & Fintech: trust is the product, monetization is the by-product","text":"Domain 4 is the only domain in the flywheel that moves trust (T) as its primary lever and converts moat strength into cash. Every other domain manufactures interactions, breadth, or liquidity and hopes trust follows; Payments manufactures trust deliberately, prices it, and sells it back to the rest of the platform. In the moat identity M = D × B × L × T, Payments is the term-owner for T and the co-owner — with D6 — of the mechanism that turns a high M into revenue. That dual role is why the register of this section is different from the others: it is written half as a trust-engineering document and half as a monetization thesis, because at Kepler those are the same document read from two ends.\n\nThe governing thought insists that Payments is not a business; it is a closing device. Mobility (D1) generates the densest behavioural data in the company but cannot underwrite anything on its own"},"S-050":{"source":"Driver 1 — The payments rails: the substrate that makes every other domain cash-free","text":"The rails are the physical-world plumbing: the ledger, the PSP and scheme connections, the KYC gate, and the settlement engine. If the rails are slow, fragmented, or per-domain, the flywheel leaks — every domain rebuilds its own money-movement stack and the shared trust signal never accumulates in one place. The strategic claim of Driver 1 is that one ledger for all six domains is worth more than six optimised ledgers, because the value is in the join, not in any single flow."},"S-051":{"source":"Mechanism 1.1 — A single unified ledger as the system of record","text":"Kepler runs one double-entry ledger that every domain posts into: a ride from D1, a charge from D2, a delivery payout to a D3 courier, a device instalment from D5 — all land as entries against the same account graph. This is the mechanism that lets Payments see the whole customer. A rider who also couriers and leases a device is one node with three revenue streams and one risk profile, not three anonymous flows in three systems. Trace S-401 records the design decision: the ledger is append-only, event-sourced, and the source of truth for both money movement and the behavioural features D6 later consumes. The architecture below shows how flows converge.\n\nThe load-bearing nodes: INGRESS API normalises every domain's payment intent into one schema; the RISK node calls D6 in-line (fraud model, ~40ms budget); the KYC/KYB GATE enforces tiered identity (tier 0 anonymous wallet top-up, tier 3 fu"},"S-052":{"source":"Mechanism 1.2 — PSP orchestration and local-rail routing","text":"No single scheme covers 14 countries economically. Kepler orchestrates across card schemes, local instant-payment rails (UPI in India, PIX in Brazil, PayNow in Singapore), and bank-transfer/RTP networks, routing each transaction to the cheapest rail that clears the risk bar. The mechanism chains directly out of 1.1: because the ledger is unified, the router can make a portfolio decision — accept slightly higher fraud on a low-margin D3 courier payout routed over a cheap local rail, because the same user's D1 ride history (fed in via S-402) collateralises the risk. Trace S-403 captures the routing economics: shifting 22 points of volume from card schemes to local rails cut blended cost-of-payment from 1.9% to 1.3% of TPV without raising realised fraud, because the risk headroom came from cross-domain data, not from the rail itself."},"S-053":{"source":"Mechanism 1.3 — Cash-free closure of D1 and D3","text":"Here Driver 1 hands off to the flywheel. Once the rails are unified and cheap, Kepler can make mobility and logistics cash-free — no driver handling notes, no courier reconciling coins. This is the first cross-domain coupling: removing cash raises D1's interaction density (D) because more low-value rides become viable, and raises D3's network liquidity (L) because couriers get paid instantly and stay on the platform. Trace S-404: in the six cities where cash was fully removed, D1 ride frequency rose 11% and D3 courier churn fell 9pp — neither number belongs to Payments' P&L, which is precisely the point. Payments spent margin to buy density and liquidity for other domains, and the moat identity M rose even though Domain 4's standalone contribution looked flat. A conglomerate scorecard would have killed this trade."},"S-054":{"source":"Driver 2 — Credit & underwriting: lending on data no bank can see","text":"If the rails make Kepler a payments company, the credit engine makes it a fintech. Driver 2 takes the unified ledger from Driver 1 and does the thing banks cannot: it underwrites 28.4m actives using behavioural collateral — how reliably you ride, charge, deliver, and pay — rather than a thin or absent credit file. This is where T compounds into monetization, because trust that is measured can be lent against."},"S-055":{"source":"Mechanism 2.1 — Behavioural underwriting off D1 and D3 exhaust","text":"The core mechanism: Kepler scores creditworthiness from platform behaviour that is exogenous to any credit bureau. A D3 courier with 18 months of on-time deliveries and stable D1 commuting patterns is a better risk than her thin bureau file suggests. This is the second cross-domain coupling — Payments underwrites on D1 mobility regularity and D3 logistics reliability. Trace S-405 documents the lift: adding cross-domain behavioural features cut the Gini-normalised default rate 210bps at constant approval, or equivalently raised approvals 14% at constant loss. The scoring logic lives in D6's feature store but is owned, productised, and priced by D4.\n\nTrace S-406 is the query itself; note the thick_file flag — a user is \"thick\" not because a bureau has data on them but because Kepler does, across domains. That is the underwriting moat in one boolean."},"S-056":{"source":"Mechanism 2.2 — Working-capital and instalment products that recycle into the flywheel","text":"The score from 2.1 powers three products: courier working-capital advances (D3), device instalments (D5), and consumer BNPL on rides/charges (D1/D2). The chaining matters: a device instalment (D5) puts a proprietary-sensor device (which raises data breadth B) into a user's hands who could not have paid upfront — so credit manufactures moat inputs for other domains. Trace S-407: instalment financing raised D5 device attach among the bottom two income quartiles by 31%, directly feeding D5's breadth term. Credit here is not a yield product; it is a distribution subsidy for the moat, repaid by better data."},"S-057":{"source":"Mechanism 2.3 — Portfolio risk and the loss-provisioning discipline","text":"Underwriting on behaviour is powerful and pro-cyclical — the same D1/D3 signals that predict good times can turn together in a downturn. Driver 2 therefore hands a risk to Driver 3: correlated behavioural default. Trace S-408 sets the guardrail — exposure is capped per cohort and provisioned against a stressed scenario where D1 ride frequency and D3 job volume fall together (the correlation the cross-domain data itself reveals). The credit engine's edge and its systemic risk come from the same source, which is the honest version of the thesis."},"S-058":{"source":"Driver 3 — Trust, fraud & compliance: the term-owner mechanism for T","text":"This is the driver that literally moves T in the moat identity. Fraud losses and compliance failures are trust leaks; every prevented fraud and every clean audit is trust retained and re-lent to all six domains. Driver 3 takes the credit exposure from Driver 2 and the payment flows from Driver 1 and defends both — using signals it does not itself generate."},"S-059":{"source":"Mechanism 3.1 — Real-time fraud scoring on D6 signals fed by D1 and D5","text":"The fraud engine scores every transaction in the ~40ms RISK node from Driver 1's architecture. Its features are the third and fourth cross-domain couplings: fraud signals from D6, which are themselves assembled from D1 location telemetry (is this ride's device physically where the card says it is?) and D5 device fingerprints (is this the same hardware that onboarded?). A card-not-present transaction that geolocates 300km from the user's D1 device is scored differently from one that sits inside their normal mobility envelope. Trace S-409: cross-domain fraud features cut fraud basis points from 18 to 7 bps of TPV while lowering the false-positive decline rate 22% — trust up on both sides of the ledger, which is the rare win where fewer good customers are wrongly blocked and fewer bad ones get through.\n\nTrace S-410 is the config. Two design choices carry the thesis: the default response to "},"S-060":{"source":"Mechanism 3.2 — Compliance, licensing, and the 14-country perimeter","text":"Trust is also regulatory. Kepler holds or passports payment/e-money and lending licences across 14 countries, and Driver 3 owns the reconciliation and reporting node from the architecture. The mechanism chains from 3.1: the same identity graph that powers fraud scoring powers KYC/KYB and sanctions screening, so compliance is a reuse of the trust infrastructure, not a parallel cost. Trace S-411: consolidating KYC across domains (one verified identity reused by D1, D3, D4, D5) cut per-user onboarding cost 38% and — more importantly — made the identity itself a moat asset, because a once-verified Kepler user onboards into every new domain with zero incremental friction. That is trust as distribution."},"S-061":{"source":"Driver 4 — Monetization & interchange: turning a high M into cash","text":"The final driver extracts money from the trust the first three built. It takes the defended, underwritten, cash-free flows and monetises them through interchange, take-rates, credit yield, and — increasingly — data-adjacent products. The strategic subtlety: interchange is regulated and varies by region, so the monetization ceiling is set by policy, not ambition, and the durable margin comes from the parts of the stack regulators do not cap."},"S-062":{"source":"Mechanism 4.1 — Interchange capture within regulated caps","text":"Regulatory / interchange NOTE — S-412. Interchange is asymmetrically capped across Kepler's footprint, and the monetization model must respect it region-by-region:\n\nEU/EEA: hard caps under the Interchange Fee Regulation — 0.20% debit, 0.30% credit. Little room; monetize on volume and adjacencies, not rate.\n\nSingapore / much of SE Asia: no hard statutory cap but scheme-set and competitive; effective blended ~0.5–0.9%.\n\nIndia (UPI): merchant-side MDR on UPI is effectively zero by policy — monetization here is never interchange; it is credit, float, and value-added services.\n\nBrazil (PIX): instant-payment rail with no interchange; Central Bank actively compresses card economics. Same conclusion as India.\n\nUS-style uncapped credit interchange (~1.8–2.2%) does not exist in Kepler's markets — the model must not assume it. Implication: in half of Kepler's TPV, interchange is legally near-zero. "},"S-063":{"source":"Mechanism 4.2 — Take-rate, float, and the blended monetization stack","text":"Kepler monetizes across four layers, each with a different regulatory exposure. The table makes the stack legible and shows where margin is durable.\n\nTrace S-413: the two high-durability layers (credit yield and float/services) already contribute 61% of Payments gross profit despite being under 40% of TPV — evidence that the monetization has already migrated off the regulated swipe toward the trust-moated products. The statement mockup below is where the user experiences all four layers at once.\n\nThe mockup is a trust artefact as much as a financial one: the score is visible and moving, the APR fell because behaviour earned it (the credit engine talking to the customer), and the fraud line advertises that protection ran without wrongly blocking her. The statement is where T is made felt. Trace S-414 notes that surfacing the earned-APR line lifted repeat credit uptake 17% — trust, once sh"},"S-064":{"source":"Mechanism 4.3 — The ledger as monetization evidence","text":"Underneath the statement sits the raw ledger — the same one from Driver 1, now read as a monetization record. The table below shows how a single day's mixed flows carry different margins, and how the join (one user, many domains) is what makes the portfolio work.\n\nTrace S-415: read across the user column and the monetization thesis appears — rivera_a and courier_301 each touch three domains in one day, and the high-margin entries (credit yield at 700–1240 bps) are only underwritable because the low-margin entries (rides, jobs) supplied the behavioural collateral. The cheap flows are the moat; the expensive flows are the monetization; the ledger is the join that makes one pay for the other. Trace S-416 closes the loop: contribution per interaction inside Payments moved from −0.19 over the trailing period, the clearest single proof point that the flywheel's target path from −0.31 blended i"},"S-065":{"source":"What's true vs what counts","text":"What's true. Payments is the fastest-growing domain (+58% yoy), it now earns most of its gross profit from durable, un-capped layers (S-413), and its per-interaction contribution has already turned positive (S-416). Interchange is legally near-zero across half of Kepler's TPV (S-412), so the standalone \"payments company\" framing is not just incomplete — it is impossible in these markets. On a monoline basis Kepler Payments would trail a focused regional PSP on rate and a focused lender on scale.\n\nWhat counts. None of the durable margin exists without the other five domains. The credit engine underwrites on D1 mobility regularity and D3 courier reliability (S-405, S-406); the fraud engine defends on D6 signals built from D1 telemetry and D5 fingerprints (S-409, S-410); the rails close the loop by making D1 and D3 cash-free, buying density and liquidity that never show up on Payments' own "},"S-066":{"source":"Domain 5 — Devices & Hardware: we sell hardware to harvest data no one else has","text":"Devices is the domain most often misread as the weakest link in the Kepler portfolio, and the misreading is instructive. On a standalone basis it is a low-margin consumer-electronics and industrial-sensor business — a category the market has spent two decades learning to value at single-digit multiples, priced on unit economics, channel, and refresh cycles. Read that way, Devices is a drag: it consumes working capital, it carries inventory risk, it lives and dies on a bill of materials measured in cents, and it will never out-margin a payments network or out-scale a mobility fleet. If Kepler were six businesses, Devices would be the one a focus-minded activist spins out first.\n\nThat is exactly why it is in the portfolio, and exactly why it is misunderstood. In the moat identity\n\nDevices is the domain that owns data breadth (B) — the width of the sensor manifold that every other domain's "},"S-067":{"source":"Driver 1 — The product line: four form factors, one sensor manifold","text":"The product strategy is deliberately not a consumer-electronics strategy. Kepler builds the minimum number of form factors required to place its sensor manifold into the maximum number of high-signal physical contexts. There are four, and they are designed as one modular platform rather than four products."},"S-068":{"source":"Mechanism 1.1 — The manifold-first design rule (S-501)","text":"Every Kepler device is architected around a shared sensor-and-compute core — the Kepler Sensor Module (KSM) — with form-factor-specific carrier boards and enclosures wrapped around it (S-501). The KSM carries the inertial, environmental, and acoustic sensors plus an edge-inference NPU; the carrier adds the connectivity, power, and human-interface elements each context needs. This is the opposite of the consumer playbook, where each product is bespoke to hit a price point. Kepler accepts a slightly higher per-unit cost in exchange for a single validated sensor stack that produces dimensionally consistent data across every context — a road-vibration reading from a vehicle mount and from a courier's handlebar are directly comparable because they come from the same silicon and the same calibration. That comparability is what makes the breadth (B) additive rather than fragmented, and it is th"},"S-069":{"source":"Mechanism 1.2 — The product mockup: what the Beacon actually shows (S-502)","text":"The KB-1's value to the user has to be real, or the device never gets placed and the sensor never samples. The interface is therefore designed as a genuinely useful navigation-and-payments surface whose data-harvesting is invisible (S-502). Rendered:\n\nEvery element on that screen is a cross-domain coupling made visible to the user. The turn card is D1's routing model rendered locally; the \"4 min to charge\" and live bay price is D2 telemetry; \"TAP TO PAY $12.40\" is the D4 wallet executing a transaction on the device's secure element; and the air-quality and road-surface read-outs are the D5 manifold showing the user a sliver of what it is measuring — enough to feel useful, nowhere near the full sample. The design principle (S-503): give the user one visible reason to keep the device powered and mounted for every invisible stream we are collecting behind it. A device in a drawer samples no"},"S-070":{"source":"Driver 2 — BOM, cost & margin: financing a sensor network with hardware margin","text":"If the product line decides what we place and where, the cost structure decides whether the placement is affordable at fleet scale. Devices runs on a deliberately unusual margin philosophy: hardware margin exists to subsidise sensor coverage, not to maximise device profit."},"S-071":{"source":"Mechanism 2.1 — The BOM cost table and the teardown that names the sensors (S-504, S-505)","text":"The KB-1 Beacon's bill of materials is where the strategy becomes concrete. The costed BOM (S-504), at a 2m-unit annual run-rate, landed cost per unit:\n\nThe teardown / exploded view (S-505) names where each of those sits physically, because the placement of a sensor determines the quality of the sample:\n\nThe exploded view carries a decision the BOM table hides (S-506): the environmental intake vent is engineered to sit above the compute stack, thermally isolated, so the SEN-55 reads true ambient particulate rather than the device's own heat plume — a $0.40 tooling cost that protects the fidelity of a data stream worth far more than the device. The IMU is bonded rigidly to the mount interface so vibration couples through the chassis of the D1 vehicle or D3 handlebar it rides on, turning the whole vehicle into an extension of the sensor. These are the design choices that separate a sensor "},"S-072":{"source":"Mechanism 2.2 — The margin waterfall: ASP to gross margin, and why it is thin on purpose (S-507)","text":"The margin waterfall from average selling price to gross margin (S-507), per KB-1 unit:\n\nA 31% hardware gross margin is unremarkable for consumer electronics and would be a disappointment for any other Kepler domain. Held against the standalone frame, Devices looks like the portfolio's laggard. But the waterfall is measuring the wrong thing (S-508). The strategically correct denominator is not device profit; it is the fully-loaded cost of the proprietary data the device generates over its service life. A KB-1 in position for its ~30-month life emits on the order of tens of millions of sensor-seconds across five independent modalities. Financing that acquisition through a standalone sensor-network build would sit at full expense on D6's cost line — which today runs at −$420m as a cost centre. Instead, the hardware margin pre-pays it: the device sells at a positive gross margin, and the da"},"S-073":{"source":"Driver 3 — The supply chain: geography as a sensor-coverage decision","text":"A sensor network is only as broad as the units you can actually manufacture, land, and place. The supply chain is therefore not a back-office function in Devices — it is the throttle on how fast breadth (B) compounds, and it is managed as such."},"S-074":{"source":"Mechanism 3.1 — The supply-chain map: fabs, assembly, ports (S-509)","text":"The physical flow (S-509), from silicon to placement:\n\nTwo structural choices are load-bearing (S-510). First, final assembly is concentrated at Jabil Penang with ASE Kaohsiung doing SoC packaging and test — deliberately dual-region against the fab base but single-node on final assembly, trading resilience for the tighter process control that a consistent sensor calibration demands. Second, the placement leg is Kepler's own: units land at the PSA Singapore and Rotterdam hubs and then ride the D1 mobility fleet and D3 courier network into the field, rather than through third-party retail. This is the distribution coupling that a standalone device maker cannot replicate — Kepler already has vehicles and couriers moving through all 42 cities daily, so the last mile of device placement is nearly free and rides infrastructure that already exists."},"S-075":{"source":"Mechanism 3.2 — The manufacturing Gantt and the concentration risk it exposes (S-511, S-512)","text":"The ramp for the KB-1 v2 and the embedded KN-2 (S-511), quarters across FY26–FY27:\n\nThe Gantt makes one dependency unmissable (S-512): the KN-2 embedded module's mass production is gated on the D1 vehicle manufacturing line, because the Node is built into vehicles at their point of assembly, not retrofitted. This is the cross-domain coupling expressed as a schedule constraint — Devices cannot ramp its highest-breadth embedded sensor faster than Mobility ramps the vehicles it lives inside. The strategic reading is that Devices' breadth-compounding is paced by D1's fleet growth, which is precisely why sequencing (the governing thought) matters: place the sensor line and the vehicle line out of sync and the moat forms slower than the model requires. The concentration risk on Jabil Penang and the single Singapore port hub is the other edge-case the Gantt surfaces — a typhoon-season disruptio"},"S-076":{"source":"Driver 4 — Proprietary sensor data is the real product","text":"Everything above — the four form factors, the thin-on-purpose margin, the fleet-ridden supply chain — exists to serve this driver. Devices' claim on the moat is breadth (B), and this is where breadth becomes measurable value."},"S-077":{"source":"Mechanism 4.1 — The five-modality manifold and its uniqueness (S-513)","text":"The Kepler manifold captures five broad, mutually-reinforcing modalities that no competitor has jointly instrumented at fleet scale (S-513): kinematic (400 Hz 6-axis IMU — road roughness, grip torque, crash signatures), environmental (particulate, VOC, humidity — air-quality maps street-by-street), acoustic (MEMS array — failing-relay and bearing signatures for predictive maintenance), positional (dual-band GNSS at sub-metre — lane-level, not road-level), and electrical (battery-cell impedance and charger telemetry via the KN-2). The uniqueness is not any single stream — competitors buy IMUs and GNSS too — but the joint distribution: only Kepler observes all five from the same calibrated node, time-aligned, across the same 42-city fleet. That joint distribution is the raw material breadth is made of, and it is why the sample cannot be reconstructed after the fact by anyone lacking the pl"},"S-078":{"source":"Mechanism 4.2 — How breadth sharpens D6, and the value attribution (S-514, S-515)","text":"The manifold's payoff is realised in D6's models, and the couplings are specific (S-514). Kinematic road-roughness data sharpens D1's routing and ride-comfort models and feeds D2's siting (rough corridors correlate with battery-drain hotspots worth charger placement). Acoustic fault signatures drive predictive maintenance across the D1 fleet and D2 charger network, converting reactive downtime into scheduled service. Electrical telemetry from the KN-2 feeds D2's battery-health and dispatch pricing. And the on-device secure element plus placement context feed D4's fraud model — a payment tap whose device reports an impossible kinematic trajectory is a fraud signal no card network can see. The second data table quantifies the attributed lift (S-515), Kepler's internal model-improvement attribution from the sensor manifold, FY26 estimate:\n\nThe attribution table is the answer to the board's "},"S-079":{"source":"What's true vs what counts","text":"What's true. Devices is, on its own financials, the portfolio's least impressive business. A 31% hardware gross margin, real inventory and tariff risk, a supply chain with genuine concentration exposure at Penang and Singapore, and a ramp paced by the domains it depends on. Judged as a device company against a focused device company, it trails — exactly as the sum-of-the-parts frame predicts, and exactly the kind of business an activist would tell Kepler to spin out. All of that is true and none of it should be argued away.\n\nWhat counts. Devices does not exist to make money on devices; it exists to place a proprietary five-modality sensor manifold into the physical world at negative net data-acquisition cost, and to own breadth (B) in the moat identity — the one term no competitor can reconstruct after the fact, because it requires hardware already placed and already sampling. The margin"},"S-080":{"source":"Domain 6 — Data & AI Platform: the moat is not a business, it is the hub of the flywheel","text":"Every other domain section in this document ends by naming which of the four moat terms it moves and which domains it feeds. Domain 6 is where those threads are tied. It is the only domain that does not own a customer, a vehicle, a charger, a courier, or a card — and it is the only domain whose output is the moat identity itself. Read as a P&L it is an embarrassment: a −$420m cost centre, the single largest line item the conglomerate-discount bears say proves Kepler is undisciplined. Read as the spine, it is the reason the other five stop being five. Domain 6 owns and compounds data breadth (B) directly — it is the layer that turns proprietary sensor and behaviour exhaust into features no competitor can assemble — and it is the only layer that touches all four terms of\n\nbecause it is the multiplication. D1 produces density, D3 produces liquidity, D2 and D4 produce trust, D5 produces brea"},"S-081":{"source":"Driver 1 — The platform architecture: one ingestion spine, one feature store, one serving layer","text":"The first driver is the least glamorous and the most decisive: there is exactly one data platform, not six. The conglomerate failure mode is not strategic disagreement — it is six teams each standing up their own warehouse, their own feature definitions, their own model registry, so that \"rider dwell time\" means one thing in D1 and a subtly different thing in D3, and the join that would have produced a feature never happens. Domain 6's architecture exists to make that divergence structurally impossible."},"S-082":{"source":"Mechanism 1.1 — A single ingestion spine that normalises six event streams into one grammar","text":"Every physical-world interaction across the estate emits an event: a ride start, a charge session, a courier accept, a card authorisation, a device heartbeat. S-601 — all six domains publish to a single append-only event bus (Kepler calls it the Interaction Log) under one canonical schema: entity_id, geohash, t, domain, event_type, payload, trust_context. At 28.4m MAU across 42 cities, the spine ingests ~3.9bn events/day at peak. The architecture diagram below is the physical shape of the platform; every later mechanism is a path through it.\n\nThe point of one grammar is the point-in-time join (S-602): any feature can be reconstructed as it was known at decision time, so a fraud model never trains on settlement data that only existed after the authorisation. That single discipline is what lets D4 signals safely sharpen D1–D3 without leakage — a cross-feed that is impossible in a six-wareh"},"S-083":{"source":"Mechanism 1.2 — A feature store that is the physical form of data breadth (B)","text":"The Interaction Log is raw; the feature store (S-603) is where breadth B actually lives. It holds two mirrored surfaces: an offline store (columnar, for training) and an online store (key-value, sub-10ms, for serving), guaranteeing train/serve parity. A feature computed once — say geohash_demand_z_15m, the 15-minute demand z-score for a location — is available to D1 routing, D2 siting, and D3 matching from the same row. This is the mechanism by which B compounds instead of fragmenting: each new domain does not add a warehouse, it adds columns other domains can read. The schema below is the load-bearing tables.\n\nNote feat_entity.trust_score and feat_entity.pay_default_pd: those columns are written by D4 and read by D1 (to decide which riders can go cash-free) — the payments-closes-the-loop coupling, made concrete as two columns in one table."},"S-084":{"source":"Mechanism 1.3 — A serving layer that returns models to the domains that fed them","text":"Breadth is inert until it is served back. The serving layer (S-604) exposes every model behind one low-latency API with a shared contract, so a domain requests a decision (route, site, match, authorise, flag) and receives it in <60ms p95 without knowing which features or which upstream domains produced it. This is the architectural expression of \"all five draw from the hub.\" It also means a model improvement — better ETA residuals from richer D5 telemetry, say — propagates to every consumer at once, rather than being re-implemented five times. Driver 1 has now built the pipes; Driver 2 explains what flows through them and why it compounds."},"S-085":{"source":"Driver 2 — The data flywheel: how five domains' data compounds into one moat","text":"The architecture is necessary but not sufficient. A pipe that carries six streams to six destinations is still a conglomerate with good plumbing. The flywheel is the claim that each domain's data raises the value of every other domain's data super-additively — that breadth B is not the sum of six datasets but their product on shared keys. Driver 2 is the mechanism of that compounding, and its centrepiece component is the Sankey and the flywheel network graph."},"S-086":{"source":"Mechanism 2.1 — Cross-domain joins create features no single domain could hold","text":"The compounding is concrete. S-605: D1 location traces + D5 accelerometer telemetry + D3 courier GPS join on geohash × t to produce road_roughness and curb_availability features — signals that improve D1 routing and D3 drop-off ETA and D2 charger-siting (rough approach roads depress utilisation). No competitor with only a rideshare app, or only a delivery app, can compute that feature, because none holds all three streams on one key. S-606: D4 authorisation outcomes join to D1 rider history and D5 device fingerprint to lift the fraud model — a card decline pattern becomes explicable when the same entity's mobility regularity and device health are columns in the same row. The data-flow Sankey shows where breadth accumulates: the six sources are the left band, the moat is the single right node, and the ribbon widths are the share of the moat's feature value each source contributes.\n\nThat l"},"S-087":{"source":"Mechanism 2.2 — The flywheel network graph: the coherency centrepiece","text":"If the Sankey shows how much each domain feeds the moat, the network graph shows that every feed is also a return — the loop that makes the wheel a wheel. This is the single most important picture in the section: the six domains as nodes, the moat as the hub, and directed edges in both directions (raw data in, models out).\n\nS-607: the graph is directed and the strategic content is in the return edges. D1 sends traces and receives routing + safety models that raise density D by cutting deadhead miles ~11%. D4 sends fraud/settlement signals and receives a credit model that raises trust T, which is what lets D1 and D3 run cash-free. D5 sends proprietary sensor telemetry — the breadth B no competitor holds — and receives OTA/health models. Delete the hub and the picture collapses into six unconnected nodes: that is the visual proof of the governing thought. The conglomerate discount is the m"},"S-088":{"source":"Mechanism 2.3 — Compounding shows up as a rising blended contribution","text":"The flywheel's output is economic, and the number is the one the whole document is anchored to: blended contribution/interaction from −0.31 over ten years. Mechanism 2.3 attributes that swing to the moat. S-608: each 10% rise in served feature value (mostly the cross-join band) lowers the marginal cost of a mobility decision (fewer empty miles), a logistics match (higher fill), and a payment authorisation (fewer false declines) simultaneously — because all three read the same improved features. The compounding is that one investment in breadth pays out across four domains at once, which is why Domain 6's −$420m is not a cost but the price of the multiplier. Driver 3 is how that feature value becomes decisions."},"S-089":{"source":"Driver 3 — The models: turning compounded breadth into decisions that move D, L, and T","text":"Features are potential; models are the realised moat. Driver 3 is the layer where breadth B is converted into density D (routing), liquidity L (matching), and trust T (scoring, safety). The distinct components here are the model-performance charts — ROC curves and a confusion matrix with real figures — because the strategic claim (\"the models are better because the data is broader\") is only credible if the performance is shown, not asserted."},"S-090":{"source":"Mechanism 3.1 — A shared model registry so one improvement propagates to five domains","text":"S-609: models are not owned by domains; they are registered in a shared registry (S-611 lineage) and consumed via the serving API. The routing model, the matching model, and the fraud model all draw from the same feature tables, so an improvement to feat_location.demand_z — say from adding D2 charge-gap data — lifts all three at once. This is the mechanism behind \"sequence, don't silo\": a siloed org retrains three models three times on three partial datasets; the platform retrains the feature once and all models inherit it."},"S-091":{"source":"Mechanism 3.2 — Model performance demonstrably tracks data breadth","text":"The claim that breadth causes performance is testable, and Domain 6 tests it by ablation: train each model on a single-domain feature set, then on the full cross-joined set, and measure the lift. The ROC and confusion figures below are the fraud/trust model (the D4 coupling, since it is the cleanest labelled problem).\n\nS-610: the AUC moves from 0.883 (D4 data only) to 0.947 (full cross-domain) and, at a fixed 0.5% false-positive rate, recall rises from 71.2% to 89.9% — an +18.7-point improvement that comes entirely from joining D1 mobility regularity and D5 device-health features onto the D4 label. That delta is the flywheel expressed inside a single confusion matrix: the same false decline the specialist eats, Kepler catches, because the specialist does not hold the mobility and device streams. Higher recall at fixed FPR is directly trust T — fewer fraud losses and fewer false declines "},"S-092":{"source":"Mechanism 3.3 — A feature pipeline that any domain can extend but not fork","text":"The models are only as trustworthy as the features feeding them, so the pipeline is code, versioned and shared. S-612: a domain adds a feature by contributing a transform to the shared pipeline, which enforces point-in-time correctness and train/serve parity; it cannot fork a private copy. The pipeline below computes the cross-domain road_roughness feature (S-605) that three domains consume.\n\nThe feature is authored once and read by three domains; the quality gate on sensor_health is the D5 coupling made executable. Driver 3 has turned breadth into decisions; Driver 4 is why those decisions are defensible over a decade."},"S-093":{"source":"Driver 4 — The moat compounding: the M identity made real, and made uncatchable","text":"The final driver is the thesis itself. Drivers 1–3 build pipes, compound breadth, and serve models; Driver 4 states why the result is a moat — an advantage that widens rather than erodes — and ties every term of M to a mechanism above."},"S-094":{"source":"Mechanism 4.1 — Each term of M is moved by a named mechanism, and D6 multiplies them","text":"M is a product, and Domain 6 is the multiplication. The table below is the accounting: which term, which mechanism, which cross-feed, and the trajectory.\n\nS-613: because M is multiplicative, moving B by 2.4× while the other terms rise 1.5–1.9× does not add — it multiplies, so M compounds far faster than any single term. This is the mathematical core of \"one flywheel, not six\": a conglomerate adds P&Ls (linear); the flywheel multiplies moat terms (super-linear). Domain 6 is the only layer where the multiplication physically happens, on shared features."},"S-095":{"source":"Mechanism 4.2 — The moat widens with scale, so sequencing beats focus","text":"S-614: the cross-join uplift (Sankey's +19%, ROC's +18.7 pts) is a function of how many streams share a key, so it grows every time a domain is sequenced onto the platform — a focused specialist adding users gets more of the same data, while Kepler adding a domain gets a new dimension that multiplies against all existing ones. This is the edge case the bears miss: at small scale the conglomerate discount is correct (six mediocre verticals), but the moat term B has increasing returns, so there is a crossover beyond which the flywheel dominates focus. Sequencing is choosing when to cross it. S-615: the ordering matters because breadth-heavy domains (D5 devices, D1 mobility) must land before the models that monetise them (D4 credit, D3 matching), or the models train on thin data and the compounding stalls — the platform is why the sequence has a right answer."},"S-096":{"source":"Mechanism 4.3 — The cost centre is the moat's price, and it is falling per unit of M","text":"S-616: Domain 6 costs −420m is not evidence of indiscipline, it is the amortising fixed cost of the multiplier that lifts blended contribution/interaction from −0.31. The bears expense the hub; the thesis capitalises it."},"S-097":{"source":"What's true vs what counts","text":"What's true. Domain 6 is, on today's books, a −$420m cost centre that owns no customer and sells no product. Each of the other five domains, run alone, trails a focused specialist — and the market's ~35% conglomerate discount is a rational read of a sum-of-the-parts that genuinely does not clear. The platform is early: feature coverage is uneven across the 42 cities, the cross-join uplift is largest in the three dense metros and thin elsewhere, and several return-edge models (D2 siting, D5 health) are still below the performance bar their data could support. Nothing here says the six businesses are individually excellent. They are not.\n\nWhat counts. M is a product, not a sum, and Domain 6 is the only layer where the terms are multiplied on shared features rather than optimised in six warehouses. The compounding is measurable and it is not a story: +19% of served feature value lives only "},"S-098":{"source":"Synthesis — the flywheel reassembled","text":"The six domains were argued separately; the thesis is that they do not act separately. This section reassembles them into the single machine — shows the moat identity compounding from the cross-feeds, sequences the build so the compounding actually happens, stress-tests it against a world that does not cooperate, prices the discount it closes, and reduces the whole ten years to the one dependency that decides success."},"S-099":{"source":"The flywheel — how six feeders compound one moat","text":"Read M = D × B × L × T not as an equation to admire but as a wiring diagram. Each domain lifts one or two terms and hands its data to the others, so the terms multiply instead of adding:\n\nMobility (D1) drives Density to the ceiling — the most physical-world interactions per user of any surface — and hands its location and behaviour exhaust to every other domain: energy siting, logistics routing, fraud detection, device telemetry, and every model.\n\nDevices (D5) drive Breadth — proprietary sensor streams no competitor can buy — and feed them straight into the models.\n\nLogistics (D3) drives Liquidity — the two-sided network that thickens with every courier and merchant — routed by mobility's data and cleared by payments.\n\nEnergy (D2) and Payments (D4) own Trust from two directions: energy by never failing at the plug, payments by never failing with money — and payments closes the loop by ma"},"S-100":{"source":"Sequencing — the order is the strategy","text":"If the moat is in the wiring, then the strategy is the order in which you lay the wire. Build the domains in the wrong sequence and each arrives before the data that would make it work; build them in the right sequence and each arrives on top of a moat the previous ones already thickened.\n\nThe load-bearing decision is Phase I: the Data/AI platform is built first, as infrastructure, not as a business — even though it has no P&L and loses $420m a year today. Sequence it last (the intuitive order — \"prove the businesses, then connect them\") and every domain spends years hoarding data that never compounds, the terms only ever add, and Kepler is the mediocre conglomerate the market already prices. The counter-intuitive order is the whole thesis: build the hub before the spokes."},"S-101":{"source":"Scenarios — does the flywheel spin if the world resists?","text":"The +$0.31 contribution target assumes the compounding lands. It is a distribution, not a forecast, hinging on the two forces Kepler does not control — the regulatory posture toward platform data-sharing (which governs whether the cross-feeds are even legal) and the cost of capital (which governs how long Kepler can fund a hub that loses money before it compounds):\n\nBase (≈50%): data-sharing tolerated, capital patient. The cross-feeds wire up on plan, the moat compounds, contribution reaches +$0.31, and the conglomerate discount inverts to a platform premium by year 8. The flywheel case is vindicated.\n\nBull (≈20%): permissive regulation, cheap capital. The cross-feeds run at full strength and Kepler compounds faster than any single-vertical competitor can respond; contribution reaches +$0.48 and the moat becomes genuinely uncatchable — but the risk is regulatory backlash provoked by that"},"S-102":{"source":"The discount it closes","text":"The ~35% conglomerate discount is not a market error to be argued away; it is the market correctly pricing what it can see — six mediocre businesses and no visible connective tissue. The discount closes only when the cross-feeds become visible and measurable — when Kepler can show, cross-feed by cross-feed, that mobility's data measurably lowered energy's siting cost, that device sensors measurably sharpened fraud models, that the terms are multiplying, not adding. The strategy's financial objective is therefore not a margin target; it is making the flywheel legible — instrumenting and reporting the compounding so the market re-rates the connective tissue from zero to the asset it actually is. Contribution per interaction (−0.31) is the single headline metric of that legibility."},"S-103":{"source":"The one dependency","text":"Everything above hangs on one thing, and it is the same thing the sequencing already named: the Data/AI platform (D6) must be built first and funded through its loss-making years as infrastructure, before any domain's cross-feed can flow. It is the hub; without it, the spokes never connect, the terms only add, and the entire flywheel thesis collapses into the conglomerate it was meant to escape. Every other decision in this document can slip a year; this one cannot, and it is the one the market — and an impatient board staring at a −$420m cost centre — will be most tempted to cut. Cutting it is not a cost saving. It is choosing to be a conglomerate."},"S-104":{"source":"What's true, and what counts","text":"What's settled. The six businesses are real and at scale; the conglomerate discount is real; the moat identity's four terms are each measurable; and the cross-feeds are technically demonstrable domain by domain. None of that is in dispute.\n\nWhat counts. The one decision that determines the decade is whether the board funds Kepler as a flywheel — hub first, sequenced, cross-feeds instrumented and made legible — or as six businesses to be optimised or spun apart. The first multiplies four terms into an uncatchable moat and inverts the discount; the second severs the wiring and confirms the mediocrity the discount already prices. The difference between them is not capital or engineering. It is whether Kepler believes its own thesis enough to build the hub before the spokes."},"S-105":{"source":"Evidence register","text":"Traces are grouped by domain so any claim walks back to its source; the domain sections carry the detailed S-1xx…S-6xx traces inline.\n\nS-0xx — thesis & moat. The M = D×B×L×T identity, the −0.31 contribution target, the 35% conglomerate discount, the scenario distribution, the sequencing critical path. Source: strategy & the unit-economics model.\n\nS-1xx — Mobility. Fleet density, utilization, safety, rider economics, the location-data cross-feeds. Fleet & safety systems of record.\n\nS-2xx — Energy. Network utilization, dispatch, reliability, the transition scenario. Grid & operations.\n\nS-3xx — Logistics. Two-sided liquidity, courier/merchant cohorts, matching, density. Marketplace analytics.\n\nS-4xx — Payments. Rails, underwriting, fraud/compliance, interchange. Fintech & risk.\n\nS-5xx — Devices. Product, BOM/margin, supply chain, sensor-data breadth. Hardware & supply chain.\n\nS-6xx — Data/A"}};
